e**: dharma_swarm modules — what gets evolved\n./docs/prompts/STRATEGIC_PROMPT.md:160:### Pattern 2: Palantir Ontology & AIP\n./docs/prompts/STRATEGIC_PROMPT.md:184:1. Select mutable module (round-robin or priority)\n./docs/prompts/STRATEGIC_PROMPT.md:330:- Guard: Must be testable with available tools\n./docs/prompts/STRATEGIC_PROMPT.md:343:- Load: Verified claims, figure data, citation database\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:120:**System 3* -- Audit (Sporadic)**: The critical innovation. S3* bypasses normal reporting channels to directly inspect S1 operations. It exists because normal channels attenuate information -- subordinates filter bad news. S3* performs random, unannounced checks. Beer was explicit: this is NOT continuous monitoring (that would be S3). It is sporadic, unpredictable, and bypasses all management layers. Accounting audits. Safety inspections. The principle: any system that only sees what its sub-units choose to report is blind.\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:169:The `MessageBus` adds direct coordination where stigmergy is too slow. Priority-ordered message delivery (`URGENT > HIGH > NORMAL`) prevents resource contention. The `subscriptions` table enables topic-based routing -- agents subscribe to the signals relevant to their S1 domain and ignore the rest. This is variety attenuation at the S2 level.\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:185:| S3 policy enforcement | `PolicyCompiler` (immutable+mutable rules) | `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/policy_compiler.py` |\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:226:**What is missing from S3***: Beer's S3* should include genuinely unpredictable audits. Currently, every telos gate check follows the same pattern for the same input. A true S3* would:\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:266:| S5 immutable values | Telos gates Tier A (AHIMSA -- non-negotiable) | `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/telos_gates.py` |\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:267:| S5 constitutional stack | `PolicyCompiler` (immutable kernel + mutable corpus) | `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/policy_compiler.py` |\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:275:The constitutional stack (immutable kernel rules that always override mutable corpus rules) is the most direct implementation of Beer's S5 principle. Beer stated that S5 defines what the system IS, not what it does. The kernel says \"AHIMSA always blocks harm\" -- this is not a policy that can be evolved or overridden. It is identity.\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:523:- **Immutable kernel** (human-defined, AI cannot modify): AHIMSA, SATYA, CONSENT. These are the metasystem's S5 constraints.\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:524:- **Mutable corpus** (AI can evolve through Darwin Engine): operational policies, resource allocation preferences, domain-specific rules. These are the AI's own S5, operating within the kernel's constraints.\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:526:The AI earns FULLY_AUTONOMOUS status not by proving it will never make mistakes, but by proving that **its S5 (identity/values) is stable under perturbation** -- that it returns to the correct eigenstate after being disturbed. TCS provides the metric. The criteria:\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:528:1. **S5 stability**: TCS > 0.7 sustained over 1000+ decision cycles, with at least 5 significant perturbations (environmental threats, resource crises) during which TCS dipped but recovered.\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:556:The trust ladder progression is, in Beer's terms, **gradually reducing attenuators while keeping amplifiers constant**. At Level 0, attenuators are maximal (the human attenuates everything). At Level 4, attenuators are minimal (only the immutable kernel constrains). The amplifiers remain active at every level -- the system always needs to perceive more than it is allowed to do.\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:567:| 3->4 | Task completion >98% | Coordination across 10+ S1 units | Self-optimization demonstrably improves over time | Sporadic audit indistinguishable from human audit | Predicted 5+ threats correctly, 2+ with advance action | TCS >0.7 sustained 1000 cycles, stable eigenstate proven |\n./docs/telos-engine/07_VSM_GOVERNANCE.md:633:| **S5** | Policy/Identity | IdentityMonitor (TCS), immutable kernel, v7 Rules, CLAUDE.md telos, Shakti Framework | `identity.py`, `policy_compiler.py`, `CLAUDE.md`, `shakti.py` | OPERATIONAL |\n./dharma_swarm/skills.py:6:and machine-executable agent configurations.\n./docs/reports/BRIEFING.md:148:- **Immutable Dharma Layer** (telos_gates.py never self-modifies, even when Darwin Engine exists)\n./docs/reports/BRIEFING.md:154:Answer: **The Darwin Engine (Phase 2).** Self-evolving agents that read their own code, propose modifications, and accept/reject based on test results — gated by dharmic safety gates. This is the DGM paper's architecture but with Akram Vignan ethics baked in at the immutable layer.\n./dharma_swarm/skill_composer.py:330:        single context string suitable for injection into the agent's\n./dharma_swarm/tui/engine/governance.py:20:    # Keep newlines/tabs; strip other control chars.\n./scripts/legacy/overnight_controller_legacy.sh:56:    r = subprocess.run([sys.executable, '-m', 'pytest', 'tests/', '-q', '--tb=no', '-x', '--timeout=10'],\n./scripts/legacy/overnight_controller_legacy.sh:281:    r = subprocess.run([sys.executable, '-m', 'pytest', 'tests/', '-q', '--tb=no', '-x', '--timeout=10'],\n./scripts/legacy/overnight_controller_legacy.sh:338:    r = subprocess.run([sys.executable, '-m', 'pytest', 'tests/', '-q', '--tb=short', '-x', '--timeout=10'],\n./scripts/start_build_conclave.sh:58:1. Preserve product shell stability on ports 3420 and 8420.\n./docs/prompts/MEGA_PROMPT_STRANGE_LOOP.md:7:summary: 'What this is : A generative seed prompt. Paste this into a fresh Claude Code session along with the Strange Loop System plan (the 12-star 5.12b seed). This prompt establishes the ontological ground from which the plan...'\n./docs/prompts/MEGA_PROMPT_STRANGE_LOOP.md:72:  coordination_comment: 'What this is : A generative seed prompt. Paste this into a fresh Claude Code session along with the Strange Loop System plan (the 12-star 5.12b seed). This prompt establishes the ontological ground from which the plan...'\n./docs/prompts/MEGA_PROMPT_STRANGE_LOOP.md:94:**What this is**: A generative seed prompt. Paste this into a fresh Claude Code session along with the Strange Loop System plan (the 12-star 5.12b seed). This prompt establishes the ontological ground from which the plan grows into something beyond what linear engineering can produce.\n./docs/prompts/MEGA_PROMPT_STRANGE_LOOP.md:142:**Cybernetic depth**: Ashby's Law of Requisite Variety (regulatory capacity must match environmental variety). Beer's Viable System Model (five necessary subsystems for viability). Von Foerster's eigenforms (stable objects are fixed points of recursive operations). Bateson's \"difference that makes a difference.\" Maturana/Varela's autopoiesis (a living system produces the components that produce it). These are not references — they are operational principles.\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:128:**Memeplexes**: Memes rarely travel alone. They form co-adapted complexes — memeplexes — that reinforce each other. A religion is a memeplex: creation story + moral code + ritual practices + afterlife beliefs + proselytizing obligation + heresy taboos. Each meme in the complex protects and reinforces the others. The heresy taboo protects the creation story from rational scrutiny. The afterlife belief provides motivation for ritual practice. The proselytizing obligation ensures transmission. Attack any single meme in a strong memeplex and the others defend it.\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:134:**Relevance to Telos Engine**: The memeplex concept is operationally critical. The Telos Engine does not need to spread individual ideas — it needs to construct a **dharmic memeplex** that is self-reinforcing, self-protecting, and mutualistic with its hosts. The selfplex insight connects directly to the R_V research — if self-referential processing has a geometric signature, then memeplex formation and dissolution may have detectable neural/computational correlates.\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:194:- Progress is inevitable\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:282:- **Intermittent variable reinforcement**: Slot machine dynamics in social media (pull to refresh, unpredictable notifications, variable like counts) create addictive usage patterns that maximize memetic exposure. The medium is not neutral — it shapes which memes can propagate.\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:367:For AI researchers: Frame universal welfare in terms of alignment, interpretability, and robust safety — the technical language they already value.\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:375:For the general public: Frame it in terms of concrete, relatable benefits — health, education, economic security, environmental restoration. Not abstractions.\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:394:2. **Predictive power**: True models generate accurate predictions. When those predictions are validated, the model gains enormous memetic fitness. Nate Silver's initial electoral prediction success made FiveThirtyEight a memetic powerhouse. Climate scientists' predictions, increasingly validated by observable events, slowly gain memetic traction. **The Telos Engine should make specific, testable predictions and track them publicly.**\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:512:- Memetic function: Establish intellectual credibility, provide the analytical depth that supports all other content\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:519:- Distribution: Substack, Medium, guest posts on established platforms, podcast appearances\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:552:- Context: Legitimate concern about unaccountable techno-paternalism\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:611:Large corporations have legal departments, PR teams, brand guidelines, and multiple stakeholders who must approve communications. A small system can respond to events in hours, not weeks. When a major AI incident occurs, the first narrative frame to be established often becomes the default. Speed of framing is a decisive advantage in memetic competition.\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:623:Large corporations protect accumulated reputation and market position. This makes them conservative and predictable. A small system can take memetic risks — publish provocative research, make bold claims (if supported by evidence), challenge established narratives — because it has no institutional reputation to protect. It only has a telos to serve.\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:655:Telos Engine positioning: **\"Safety is necessary but not sufficient. Alignment to what?\"** Anthropic aligns AI to human preferences. The Telos Engine asks: which human preferences? When preferences conflict (as they inevitably do), what meta-principle resolves the conflict? Universal welfare is that meta-principle. Position the Telos Engine as the philosophical completion of Anthropic's technical program.\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:701:4. **Invite scrutiny.** Design every claim to be falsifiable, every system to be auditable, every argument to be challengeable. What survives scrutiny becomes stronger. What doesn't survive deserved to die.\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:723:- Begin documenting the bridge hypothesis (R_V contraction = L3 to L4 transition = swabhaav) in a format suitable for a follow-up paper or public essay.\n./docs/telos-engine/04_MEMETIC_ENGINEERING.md:726:- Establish a consistent publishing cadence (weekly Substack or equivalent) that builds audience and credibility\n./te