 - ontology\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:72:  coordination_comment: 'Date: 2026-03-14 Purpose: extract the highest-leverage patterns from Palantir Ontology and map them onto DGC so the swarm makes smarter, more defensible decisions with a quality metric that is hard to game inside the...'\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:92:# DGC Decision Ontology Upgrade\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:95:Purpose: extract the highest-leverage patterns from Palantir Ontology and map them onto DGC so the swarm makes smarter, more defensible decisions with a quality metric that is hard to game inside the system itself.\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:105:- represent logic as executable functions\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:108:That is why their Ontology is powerful. It treats decisions as a first-class operational substrate, not as after-the-fact commentary.\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:121:## What Palantir Ontology Actually Gets Right\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:125:### 1. The ontology models decisions, not just data\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:127:Palantir's architecture docs explicitly frame the Ontology as representing \"the complex, interconnected decisions of an enterprise,\" with a four-part integration of `data + logic + action + security`.\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:145:- `Mission`, `Decision`, `Evidence`, `Option`, `Metric`, and `Outcome` should be ontology objects\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:146:- `propose_decision`, `challenge_decision`, `approve_decision`, `execute_decision`, and `record_outcome` should be ontology actions\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:147:- scoring, routing, and reviewer selection should be ontology functions\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:159:### 4. Ontology evolution itself is reviewable\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:161:Palantir proposals put ontology changes on branches, require review, and then merge them into main.\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:171:Palantir couples ontology execution to lineage, observability, and granular permissions.\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:176:- they must be inspectable, attributable, replayable, and permission-scoped\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:178:## The DGC Decision Ontology\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:182:It should be a narrow ontology for swarm cognition.\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:312:  ontology mapper, external source compressor, domain synthesis.\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:329:2. `GLM + Kimi + MiniMax + Qwen` expand evidence, objections, and ontology fit.\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:387:### Phase 3: tie outcomes back into the ontology\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:405:- `dharma_swarm/decision_ontology.py`\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:406:- `tests/test_decision_ontology.py`\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:415:This is not the full ontology yet, but it is the right substrate.\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:421:- Palantir Architecture Center, The Ontology system\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:422:  https://www.palantir.com/docs/foundry/architecture-center/ontology-system/\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:423:- Palantir Ontology overview\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:424:  https://www.palantir.com/docs/foundry/ontology/overview\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:428:  https://www.palantir.com/docs/foundry/ontology-sdk/typescript-osdk\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:429:- Palantir ontology edits / function-backed actions\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:430:  https://www.palantir.com/docs/foundry/functions/typescript-v2-ontology-edits/\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:431:- Palantir ontology proposals\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:437:- Palantir ontology permissions\n./docs/reports/DGC_DECISION_ONTOLOGY_UPGRADE_2026-03-14.md:438:  https://www.palantir.com/docs/foundry/ontologies/ontology-permissions\n./docs/telos-engine/01_SATTVA_VISION.md:128:**Speed of decision.** A human project manager looking at a 10,000-hectare degraded landscape might take 6 months to produce a restoration plan. A system with access to satellite imagery, soil data, rainfall models, species databases, drone fleet availability, local labor market data, carbon price curves, and community governance structures could produce that plan in hours. Not because AI is smarter than humans at ecology -- it is not -- but because it can hold more variables simultaneously and iterate faster.\n./docs/telos-engine/01_SATTVA_VISION.md:136:1. **A real-time restoration optimizer.** Given a geographic area, the engine must integrate: satellite imagery (Sentinel-2, Planet Labs), soil maps (SoilGrids, ISRIC), rainfall projections (ERA5 reanalysis + climate models), species suitability databases (GBIF, local forest department records), carbon sequestration models (per-species allometric equations), community labor availability, drone fleet logistics, and current carbon market prices. Output: a restoration plan that maximizes welfare-tons (not just carbon), updated weekly.\n./docs/telos-engine/01_SATTVA_VISION.md:181:**Per-inference attribution actually deployed.** The carbon attribution feasibility study at `/Users/dhyana/jagat_kalyan/CARBON_ATTRIBUTION_FEASIBILITY.md` establishes that per-inference carbon tagging is technically feasible within +/-40% accuracy today. But nobody is doing it in production. Every API call from every AI company carries an ecological cost that is currently invisible. Making it visible changes behavior.\n./docs/telos-engine/01_SATTVA_VISION.md:199:By 2031: Welfare-tons are a recognized unit in at least two carbon market registries (Verra VCS and Gold Standard). 50+ AI companies use per-inference carbon attribution, generating $100M+ annually in offset demand that is routed through welfare-ton-scored projects. The price premium for welfare-tons over conventional carbon credits is established at 3-7x, proven by buyer willingness to pay.\n./docs/telos-engine/01_SATTVA_VISION.md:213:**AI music:** Suno and Udio generate full songs from text prompts. AIVA (Artificial Intelligence Virtual Artist) composes classical and cinematic music. Google's MusicLM generates music from text. Stability Audio generates tracks. None of these feel like \"having a genius collaborator\" -- they feel like vending machines. The input is a description; the output is a product. The collaborative process is missing.\n./docs/telos-engine/01_SATTVA_VISION.md:215:**AI visual art:** Midjourney, DALL-E 3, Stable Diffusion, Firefly -- extraordinary capability. But again, transactional. The artist describes what they want; the machine produces it. The back-and-forth of genuine creative collaboration -- where the collaborator surprises you, challenges your assumptions, shows you connections you missed -- is rare.\n./docs/telos-engine/01_SATTVA_VISION.md:287:3. **Kernel immutability protocol.** The 11 telos gates cannot be modified by any instance. They can be extended (a local instance might add a 12th gate specific to its cultural context) but never reduced. This is the KernelGuard mechanism from dharma_swarm applied at civilization scale: SHA-256 signed axioms that any instance can verify against the canonical set.\n./docs/