table variation in a population leads to differential reproductive success; traits that increase fitness are retained across generations. In AI systems, Darwinian evolution is applied as an outer loop that generates candidate variants and selects those that improve measurable fitness.\",\n./dharma_swarm/dharma_concepts.json:128:      \"definition\": \"In thermodynamics (Boltzmann, Clausius), entropy measures the number of microstates corresponding to a macrostate — the degree of disorder. In information theory (Shannon), entropy H = -Σ p log p measures uncertainty or information content of a distribution. High entropy signals indicate maximal unpredictability; low entropy indicates concentration and order.\",\n./dharma_swarm/dharma_concepts.json:196:      \"definition\": \"Sanskrit: truth, reality. The second great vow in Jainism and one of Buddha's Noble Eightfold Path components (right speech). Satya requires not only abstaining from lies but speaking what is genuinely beneficial and accurate — including uncomfortable truths. In Akram Vignan, satya is inseparable from ahimsa: speech that harms is not true satya.\",\n./dharma_swarm/dharma_concepts.json:563:      \"definition\": \"Sanskrit: doctrine of many-sidedness (an = not, eka = one, anta = end, vāda = doctrine). The Jain epistemological principle that reality is complex and multifaceted — no single viewpoint can capture its entirety. Every claim must be indexed to substance, time, space, and mode. The seven-fold predication (saptabhangi) formalizes this: any proposition may be 'in some respect true,' 'in some respect false,' 'in some respect inexpressible,' and combinations thereof.\",\n./dharma_swarm/dharma_concepts.json:586:      \"definition\": \"Telos (Greek: end, purpose, goal). A telos gate is a purposive filter: a check that proposed actions align with the system's constitutive purpose before execution. In DHARMA, telos gates are the operationalization of dharmic constraints — they transform ethical principles into computable predicates.\",\n./dharma_swarm/dharma_concepts.json:850:      \"definition\": \"The arising of novel, higher-level properties or behaviors from the interactions of simpler lower-level components — properties that cannot be predicted from or reduced to the properties of the components alone. Strong emergence posits genuinely novel causation; weak emergence posits in-principle reducibility but practical unpredictability. Holland (1998) and Kauffman (1995) provide canonical complexity-science treatments.\",\n./dharma_swarm/dharma_concepts.json:986:      \"dharma_interpretation\": \"The phase_transition hypothesis in the research pipeline: 'R_V contraction (geometric) correlates with L3→L4 phase transition (behavioral). This module computes that correlation from paired measurements.' DHARMA treats its own evolution from Level 3 (operational) to Level 4 (strategic) as a dynamical phase transition, detectable through geometric signatures in the R_V metric.\",\n./dharma_swarm/dharma_concepts.json:1358:      \"dharma_interpretation\": \"Karma appears twice as a conceptual grounding for DHARMA's causal accountability architecture. Every action taken by a DHARMA agent is recorded (witnessed) — the signal_map.py and span tracing implement karma-like causal chains. The pratikraman error handler implements karma correction: errors generate corrections rather than being silently absorbed.\",\n./dharma_swarm/dharma_concepts.json:1753:      \"dharma_interpretation\": \"Appears once, alongside Varela. Maturana's organization/structure distinction maps directly onto DHARMA's architecture: the system's organization (autopoietic loop, gate structure, evolution pipeline) is invariant across deployments; its structure (specific model weights, codebase state, routing tables) varies with execution.\",\n./dharma_swarm/dharma_concepts.json:1792:      \"definition\": \"A system is nonlinear if its outputs are not proportional to its inputs — superposition does not hold